Part 2

Dr. Sen was sitting at the corner table of the visitor's room.

She was fifty, perhaps fifty-two, wearing a silk saree that had the dull grey color of river silt.

She had three folders on the table, their brown cardboard covers held together by red cotton strings.

"I expected you earlier, Dr. Tripathy," she said.

Adarsh sat in the wooden chair across.

"The shift took time," he said.

"Sarita brought him here in 2016," she said. "He had been found sitting in the Alipore garage, staring at the silver sedan for eight hours without moving."

Adarsh looked at the folders.

The notes were written in a quick, clinical hand.

"He told me about Rehman," she said. "He described the canvas bag, the way the boy painted the kitchen, even his Odia accent. He said the boy had Ira's eyes."

"Ira," Adarsh said.

"He carried her memory like a stone in his shoe. Every step hurt, but he had stopped trying to shake it out."

She turned a page. The paper made a dry rustle.

"The yellow envelope was real, but it was only a municipal tax receipt. Vikram needed a reason to let the boy in. So his mind read Ira's name on the cheap yellow paper."

"Why?"

"Because he was tired of the split," she said, looking out at the hospital parking lot. "One half of him had built the fourteen hundred crore. The other half had left the anatomy lab, leaving a textbook half-underlined. He wanted the well, but the tycoon in him couldn't stop building."

She tapped the folder.

"Rehman was the alternate choice. The boy who could buy the sedan, fly to Geneva, and run the business, while Vikram slept on the wooden bench in Bagbazar. Rehman was the one who could shout at him on the terrace."

"The terrace," Adarsh said. "The candle and the sun."

"It was Vikram's own voice," she said. "He had given the empire to Rohan. He had walked away. But even in Bagbazar, the MLA still called him *Ahuja saab*. He couldn't escape the name. He was guilty that his legacy followed him."

She closed the folder.

"The real Ira Sen appearing at the press meet broke the split. The moment she said she never had a son, Rehman had to disappear."

"Did he know?" Adarsh asked.

"He knew," she said. "He told me he signed the CEO transfer with a blue blur because the space for the second name was blank. He said: *I wanted to give the pen to Rehman. But Rehman had no hand to take it.*"

She stood up.

She tied the red string around the cardboard, the knot tight and neat.

"His case was simple, Dr. Tripathy. Some minds break because they are weak. His broke because it was too honest to keep the palace and the well at the same time."

She looked at him.

"His smiles were transparent," she said. "But his tears... they had no color."

Adarsh sat in the chair.

The visitor's room was silent now.

The lawyer's deeds were in Dalhousie Square, the Alipore house locked, the factory compound gates opening and closing.

But the case file on the table was the only thing that had his friend's name written on the cover.

"Thank you, doctor," Adarsh said.

She picked up the folders and left.

Her sandals made a quiet, clicking sound against the corridor floor, fading until only the scratching sound of the ceiling fan remained in the room.

[End of Part 2]
